    <text>
        <body>
            <head>55. Personal Note Prepared by the Deputy Secretary of State (<persName
                    corresp="recrWcRZxYT57GiP4">Dam</persName>)<note n="1" place="foot"
                    type="source" xml:id="d55fn1">Source: Department of State, Executive
                    Secretariat, <gloss target="#t_SSI_1">S/S–I</gloss> Records: Deputy Secretary
                        <persName corresp="recrWcRZxYT57GiP4">Dam</persName>’s Official Files, Lot
                    85D308, Personal Notes of Deputy Secretary—<persName corresp="recrWcRZxYT57GiP4"
                        >Kenneth W. Dam</persName>—Oct. 1982—Sept. 1983. Secret. Dictated on
                    February 28.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1983-02-28"
                        >February 28, 1983</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>[Omitted here is material not related to <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs>
                </gloss>.]</p>
            <p>At 10 o’clock my <rs corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic">arms control</rs>
                discussion group met.<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d55fn2">No other record of
                    this meeting was found.</note> General <persName corresp="rec1BYpVimWguCga9"
                    >Scowcroft</persName> attended. He is currently heading the <gloss
                    target="#t_MX_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec99k2btquR4fVXS" type="topic">MX</rs>
                </gloss> Commission.<note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d55fn3">Reference is to the
                        <orgName corresp="recilTL8Sxklv18up">President’s Commission on Strategic
                        Forces</orgName>, which Reagan established on January 3 to “review the
                    strategic <rs corresp="recbm2CDfl6YlSCnq">modernization</rs> program with
                    particular focus on our land-based <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic"
                        >intercontinental ballistic missile</rs> and basing alternatives for that
                    system.” (“Statement Announcing the Establishment and Membership of the <orgName
                        corresp="recilTL8Sxklv18up">President’s Commission on Strategic
                        Forces</orgName>, and Designation of Chairman and Vice Chairman,” <hi
                        rendition="simple_italic">Public Papers: Reagan</hi>, 1983, vol. I, pp. 4–5)
                    Documentation pertaining to the <orgName corresp="recilTL8Sxklv18up">President’s
                        Commission on Strategic Forces</orgName> is scheduled for publication in
                        <ref target="frus1981-88v43">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988, vol. XLIII,
                        National Security Policy, 1981–1984</ref>.</note> We discussed what the
                Commission might report and what impact it might have on <rs
                    corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic">arms control</rs>. It is clear that the
                interest in <rs corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic">arms control</rs> is very
                high on <orgName corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM">Capitol Hill</orgName>, although the
                content of the concerns and hopes appears to be low. Part of the reason is that the
                    <orgName corresp="recStxd9xhgoem3dN">Republicans</orgName> are concerned about
                the 1984 election and feel that the <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq"
                    >President</persName> needs some breakthrough on the <rs
                    corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic">arms control</rs> front, but the
                Republican Members fear that the <rs corresp="recrvfeHjk0YIZ1si" type="event"
                    >Administration</rs> is not serious about <rs corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl"
                    type="topic">arms control</rs> negotiations. Recently there was a test of a new
                Soviet missile, giving rise to concerns about the possibility that the Soviets might
                be in violation, at least in spirit, of the provision in the <gloss
                    target="#t_SALT_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec6OIA4luUvtBKNn" type="event">SALT</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs corresp="recF3SBVeQQW0d1aM" type="agreement-or-mandate">II</rs> agreement
                providing for only one new missile. Meanwhile, it is expected that the <gloss
                    target="#t_MX_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec99k2btquR4fVXS" type="topic">MX</rs>
                </gloss> Commission will recommend deployment of <gloss target="#t_MX_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec99k2btquR4fVXS" type="topic">MX</rs>
                </gloss> missiles, perhaps only 50 as opposed to the 100 originally planned, in <rs
                    corresp="recJIrLOK12134vZd" type="topic">Minuteman</rs> silos with development
                and eventual deployment of a new small mobile missile system. That would mean that
                the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">United States</placeName> would have two
                new types. Obviously this recommendation, which is an alternative to closely spaced
                basing and in particular to the dense pack approach, will run into objections that
                it is in violation of <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec6OIA4luUvtBKNn" type="event">SALT</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs corresp="recF3SBVeQQW0d1aM" type="agreement-or-mandate">II</rs>. This will be
                true even though the small mobile missile cannot be deployed until long after <gloss
                    target="#t_SALT_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec6OIA4luUvtBKNn" type="event">SALT</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs corresp="recF3SBVeQQW0d1aM" type="agreement-or-mandate">II</rs> would have
                expired by its terms.</p>
            <p>[Omitted here is material not related to <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O" type="event">START</rs>
                </gloss>.]</p>
